SIMPLE: trail
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trail
<hw>Trail</hw> <pr>(tr⟦amac⟧l)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Trailed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Trailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trailen</ets>, OF. <ets>trailler</ets> to trail a deer, or hunt him
upon a cold scent, also, to hunt or pursue him with a limehound, F.
<ets>trailler</ets> to trail a fishing line; probably from a derivative
of L. <ets>trahere</ets> to draw; cf. L. <ets>traha</ets> a drag,
sledge, <ets>tragula</ets> a kind of drag net, a small sledge, Sp.
<ets>trailla</ets> a leash, an instrument for leveling the ground, D.
<ets>treilen</ets> to draw with a rope, to tow, <ets>treil</ets> a rope
for drawing a boat. See <er>Trace</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>To hunt by the track; to track.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>to follow behind.</def> <sd>(c)</sd> <def>To
pursue.</def> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To draw or drag, as along the ground.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And hung his head, and <qex>trailed</qex> his legs along.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They shall not <qex>trail</qex> me through their streets⟦br⟧
Like a wild beast.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Long behind he <qex>trails</qex> his pompous robe.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>To carry, as a firearm, with the
breech near the ground and the upper part inclined forward, the piece
being held by the right hand near the middle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To tread down, as grass, by walking through it; to
lay flat.</def> <rj><au>Longfellow.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To take advantage of the ignorance of; to impose
upon.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I presently perceived she was (what is vernacularly termed)
<qex>trailing</qex> Mrs. Dent; that is, playing on her ignorance.</q>
<rj><qau>C. Bronte.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trail
<hw>Trail</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be
drawn out in length; to follow after.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When his brother saw the red blood <qex>trail</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To grow to great length, especially when slender and
creeping upon the ground, as a plant; to run or climb.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trail</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Trail
<hw>Trail</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A track left by man or
beast; a track followed by the hunter; a scent on the ground by the
animal pursued; <as>as, a deer <ex>trail</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They traveled in the bed of the brook, leaving no dangerous
<qex>trail</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Cooper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How cheerfully on the false <qex>trail</qex> they cry!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A footpath or road track through a wilderness or
wild region; <as>as, an Indian <ex>trail</ex> over the
plains</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Anything drawn out to a length; <as>as, the
<ex>trail</ex> of a meteor; a <ex>trail</ex> of smoke.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When lightning shoots in glittering <qex>trails</qex> along.</q>
<rj><qau>Rowe.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything drawn behind in long undulations; a
train.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A radiant <xex>trail</xex> of hair.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Anything drawn along, as a vehicle.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A frame for trailing plants; a trellis.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The entrails of a fowl, especially of game, as the
woodcock, and the like; -- applied also, sometimes, to the entrails of
sheep.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The woodcock is a favorite with epicures, and served with its
<qex>trail</qex> in, is a delicious dish.</q>
<rj><qau>Baird.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <fld>(Mil.)</fld> <def>That part of the stock of a gun
carriage which rests on the ground when the piece is unlimbered. See
<xex>Illust.</xex> of <cref>Gun carriage</cref>, under
<er>Gun</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <def>The act of taking advantage of the ignorance of a
person; an imposition.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Trail boards</b></col> <fld>(Shipbuilding)</fld>, <cd>the
carved boards on both sides of the cutwater near the figurehead.</cd> --
<col><b>Trail net</b></col>, <cd>a net that is trailed or drawn behind a
boat.</cd> <rj><au>Wright.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trailer</ent>⟦br⟧
